SIMPLE: ridicule
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Ridicule
<hw>Rid"i*cule</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F.
<ets>ridicule</ets>, L. <ets>ridiculum</ets> a jest, fr.
<ets>ridiculus</ets>. See <er>Ridiculous</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>An object of sport or laughter; a laughingstock; a laughing
matter.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>[Marlborough] was so miserably ignorant, that his deficiencies
made him the <qex>ridicule</qex> of his contemporaries.</q>
<rj><qau>Buckle.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To the people . . . but a trifle, to the king but a
<qex>ridicule</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Foxe.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Remarks concerning a subject or a person designed to
excite laughter with a degree of contempt; wit of that species which
provokes contemptuous laughter; disparagement by making a person an
object of laughter; banter; -- a term lighter than
<xex>derision</xex>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>We have in great measure restricted the meaning of
<qex>ridicule</qex>, which would properly extend over whole region of
the ridiculous, -- the laughable, -- and we have narrowed it so that in
common usage it mostly corresponds to ⟦ldquo⟧derision⟦rdquo⟧, which does
indeed involve personal and offensive feelings.</q>
<rj><qau>Hare.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Safe from the bar, the pulpit, and the throne,⟦br⟧
Yet touched and shamed by <qex>ridicule</qex> alone.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Quality of being ridiculous; ridiculousness.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To see the <qex>ridicule</qex> of this practice.</q>
<rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Derision; banter; raillery; burlesque; mockery;
irony; satire; sarcasm; gibe; jeer; sneer; ribbing.</syn> <usage> --
<er>Ridicule</er>, <er>Derision</er>, <er>mockery</er>,
<er>ribbing</er>: All four words imply disapprobation; but
<xex>ridicule</xex> and <xex>mockery</xex> may signify either
good-natured opposition without manifest malice, or more maliciously, an
attempt to humiliate. <xex>Derision</xex> is commonly bitter and
scornful, and sometimes malignant. <er>ribbing</er> is almost always
good-natured and fun-loving.</usage>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Ridicule</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Ridicule
<hw>Rid"i*cule</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Ridiculed</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>;<pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Ridiculing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <def>To laugh at mockingly or
disparagingly; to awaken ridicule toward or respecting.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I 've known the young, who <qex>ridiculed</qex> his rage.</q>
<rj><qau>Goldsmith.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To deride; banter; rally; burlesque; mock;
satirize; lampoon. See <er>Deride</er>.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 1241 --></p>

<p><ent>Ridicule</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Ridicule
<hw>Rid"i*cule</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[F.]</ety>
<def>Ridiculous.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>This action . . . became so <qex>ridicule</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Aubrey.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Ridiculer</ent>⟦br⟧
